Note that Legacy Defects and Ambiguous Interpretations have resolution
paths that don't involve code changes to NoUI. Legacy defects are
resolved by documenting the finding---they are a value-add delivery to
the agency. Ambiguous interpretations are escalated to the authority
that can make the determination (plan counsel or board). In both cases,
the defect lifecycle still applies: the defect moves through OPEN →
IN_PROGRESS → AWAITING_REVIEW → RESOLVED → VERIFIED even though the
resolution is a document rather than a code change.

4\. Prioritized Backlog

All open defects exist in a single prioritized queue. There is no
separate "known issues" list, no hidden backlog, and no informal
tracking. If a defect exists, it is in this queue, it has a priority,
and it is visible on the Layer 3 dashboard.

4.1 Priority Assignment

Priority is automatically derived from the severity × member impact
scope matrix defined in Layer 1, Section 2.4. Manual priority overrides
are permitted only by the Technical Director or Benefits Supervisor, and
require a documented justification. A downgrade from the matrix-derived
priority must explain why the defect is less urgent than its
classification suggests. An upgrade is always permitted without
justification.

4.2 Queue Ordering

Within each priority level, defects are ordered by three tiebreaker
criteria applied in sequence:

1.  **Age (oldest first).** Defects that have been open longest are
    worked first. This prevents the anti-pattern where new, interesting
    defects push older items further down the queue.

2.  **Member impact count (highest first).** A defect affecting 5,000
    Tier 1 members takes precedence over one affecting 200 Tier 3
    members at the same priority level.

3.  **Demo case association (associated first).** Defects that affect
    rules exercised by the four demo cases are prioritized because they
    are the most visible proof points.

