5\. Resolution Workflow

This section defines the step-by-step workflow for resolving a defect,
from discovery through verified closure. The workflow integrates with
the controlled deployment process from Layer 1 and the test execution
pipeline from Layer 2.

5.1 Expedited Path (P0 and P1)

Critical and immediate-priority defects follow an expedited path that
compresses the standard workflow without skipping any verification step:

4.  **Detection:** Defect is detected by test pipeline, data quality
    engine, or manual report. Classified as P0 or P1. Dashboard goes
    RED. Alert sent immediately.

5.  **Triage (\< 30 minutes):** Technical Director confirms
    classification. For P0: identifies affected case types and issues
    processing halt order. For P1: confirms no active benefits are
    affected.

6.  **Root cause analysis:** Trace the defect to its origin using the
    failure report (Layer 2, Section 6.2). Identify the exact rule,
    calculation, data, or integration point that is wrong. Document the
    root cause.

7.  **Fix implementation (test environment):** Implement the fix in the
    test environment. Run all affected tests plus full regression. For
    P0: regression must complete cleanly with zero failures.

8.  **Change package assembly:** Package includes: code diff, root cause
    analysis, affected test results, full regression results, rollback
    procedure.

9.  **Human review:** Technical Director reviews the complete package.
    For rule changes, this is the certification step from the SDLC. The
    review confirms the fix addresses the root cause (not just the
    symptom) and introduces no new risk.

10. **Staged deployment:** Deploy to staging. Four demo cases run
    against staging. All pass.

11. **Production deployment:** Deploy to production. Affected tests run
    against production. Post-deployment verification confirms the fix.

12. **Monitoring window:** Enhanced Data Quality Engine scan focused on
    the affected rules/data for 24--48 hours.

13. **Closure:** If monitoring window is clean, defect moves to
    VERIFIED. Dashboard updates. For P0: processing halt lifted for
    affected case types.

The entire expedited path for a P0 defect targets same-business-day
resolution. Elapsed time is tracked and reported as a quality metric.

5.2 Standard Path (P2 through P4)

Lower-priority defects follow the same logical sequence but are
scheduled within sprint capacity rather than treated as emergencies:

14. **Backlog entry:** Defect enters the prioritized queue at its
    derived position. SLA timer begins.

15. **Sprint planning:** Defects are pulled into the active sprint based
    on priority and capacity. P2 defects are pulled first, then P3. P4
    items are pulled when capacity permits.

16. **Investigation and fix:** Same root cause analysis and fix
    implementation as the expedited path, but within the sprint
    timeline.

17. **Review and deployment:** Same controlled deployment process. No
    corners cut---the verification requirements are identical regardless
    of priority.

18. **Verification and closure:** Post-deployment verification.
    Monitoring window. Defect moves to VERIFIED.

> *The difference between expedited and standard paths is scheduling,
> not rigor. A P4 defect receives the same test coverage, review gate,
> and deployment verification as a P0. The only difference is when the
> work happens.*

6\. Special Resolution Procedures

Certain defect categories require specialized handling beyond the
standard workflow.

6.1 Data Quality Defects

Data quality defects are unique because NoUI does not have authority to
correct the data. Per ADR-005, all data corrections require human agency
approval. The resolution workflow is:

19. **Discovery:** Data Quality Engine identifies the finding and
    classifies it by severity.

20. **Evidence assembly:** The system prepares a finding package: the
    affected member(s), the evidence of the data issue, the proposed
    correction, and the impact assessment (what calculations would
    change if the data is corrected).

21. **Agency review:** The finding is presented to agency staff through
    the workspace. Resolution categories: proposed correction (awaiting
    review), requires research, requires agency decision.

22. **Agency action:** Agency applies the correction in the source
    system (or declines). NoUI does not modify the data.

23. **Verification:** After agency correction, NoUI re-runs the affected
    calculations to confirm the data quality issue is resolved.

Data quality defects may have long resolution times because they depend
on agency action. The SLA timer reflects this: the timer pauses when the
defect is in "awaiting agency review" status, resuming when the agency
responds. However, aging is still tracked and visible on the
dashboard---a data quality finding that has been waiting 60 days for
agency review is flagged for follow-up.

6.2 Ambiguous Interpretations

When a governing document provision is unclear and multiple
interpretations are defensible, the defect requires escalation to an
authority that can provide a definitive interpretation: plan counsel,
actuarial consultant, or the board of trustees. The resolution workflow
is:

24. **Documentation:** Prepare an interpretation memo that presents the
    ambiguous language, two or more candidate interpretations, the
    mathematical impact of each interpretation (using demo case members
    as examples), and a recommendation.

25. **Escalation:** Submit the memo to the appropriate authority. For
    statutory ambiguity: plan counsel. For policy ambiguity: Executive
    Director or board.

26. **Interim handling:** While awaiting the authoritative
    determination, the system implements the most conservative
    interpretation (the one that results in the lower benefit amount,
    protecting the trust fund). This is documented as an assumption with
    a Q-CALC reference.

27. **Resolution:** When the authority responds, the rule is updated
    through the full SDLC. If the interim interpretation was correct, no
    code change is needed---just a status change from ASSUMED to
    CONFIRMED. If it was incorrect, the rule change follows the standard
    SDLC path.

6.3 Cascading Defects

A defect in one rule can cascade to affect other rules that depend on
it. For example, a defect in the AMS calculation affects every benefit
formula that uses AMS as an input. Cascading defects require:

-   **Impact mapping:** Trace all downstream rules that consume the
    affected output using the cross-rule interaction matrix (Layer 2,
    Section 4.2).

-   **Scope assessment:** Re-evaluate the member impact scope. A defect
    originally classified as Cohort may be Plan-Wide once cascading
    effects are traced.

-   **Priority re-evaluation:** The cascading scope may elevate the
    priority from the original matrix-derived level.

-   **Batch verification:** After the root cause fix, all downstream
    calculations are re-verified, not just the primary rule.

7\. Fix Verification Protocol

Verification is the most critical step in the resolution workflow. A fix
that is declared "done" without rigorous verification is not a fix---it
is a hope. The verification protocol defines what must be true before a
defect can move to VERIFIED status.

7.1 Verification Checklist

  -------- ---------------------------------------- -------------------------
  **\#**   **Verification Item**                    **Evidence**

  1        The original failing test now passes     Test execution log
           against the hand-calculated oracle       showing pass with oracle
                                                    citation

  2        A new regression test exists that        Test case in the
           specifically targets the defect scenario repository with the
                                                    defect ID in the comment

  3        Full regression suite passes with zero   Regression report
           failures                                 attached to the change
                                                    package

  4        All four demo cases pass in the test     Acceptance test log
           environment                              

  5        The fix has been deployed to staging and Staging deployment log +
           all tests pass in staging                staging test results

  6        The fix has been deployed to production  Production deployment log

  7        Post-deployment verification passes in   Production test execution
           production                               log

  8        24--48 hour monitoring window shows no   Data Quality Engine scan
           anomalies                                results for the
                                                    monitoring window

  9        No related defects were introduced       Cross-rule impact
           (check for cascading impact)             analysis from the change
                                                    package

  10       The defect record is updated with        Defect record in the
           resolution notes, root cause, and fix    backlog system
           description                              
  -------- ---------------------------------------- -------------------------

> *Every item on this checklist must be satisfied. Partial
> verification---"unit tests pass but we haven't done regression
> yet"---is not verification. The defect remains IN_PROGRESS until all
> items are complete.*

